# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: physical-design-vlsi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] In electronic design automation, a **design rule** is a geometric constraint imposed on circuit board, semiconductor device, and integrated circuit (IC) designers to ensure their designs function properly, reliably, and can be produced with acceptable yield.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Design rules for production are developed by process engineers based on the capability of their processes to realize design intent.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Electronic design automation is used extensively to ensure that designers do not violate design rules; a process called **design rule checking** (**DRC**).
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] DRC is a major step during physical verification signoff on the design, which also involves LVS (layout versus schematic) checks, XOR checks, ERC (electrical rule check), and antenna checks.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] The importance of design rules and DRC is greatest for ICs, which have micro- or nano-scale geometries; for advanced processes, some fabs also insist upon the use of more restricted rules to improve yield.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Design rules are a series of parameters provided by semiconductor manufacturers that enable the designer to verify the correctness of a mask set.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Design rules are specific to a particular semiconductor manufacturing process.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] A design rule set specifies certain geometric and connectivity restrictions to ensure sufficient margins to account for variability in semiconductor manufacturing processes, so as to ensure that most of the parts work correctly.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] The most basic design rules are shown in the diagram on the right.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] A *width* rule specifies the minimum width of any shape in the design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] A *spacing* rule specifies the minimum distance between two adjacent objects.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] These rules will exist for each layer of semiconductor manufacturing process, with the lowest layers having the smallest rules (typically 100 nm as of 2007) and the highest metal layers having larger rules (perhaps 400 nm as of 2007).
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] A two layer rule specifies a relationship that must exist between two layers.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] For example, an *enclosure* rule might specify that an object of one type, such as a contact or via, must be covered, with some additional margin, by a metal layer.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] A typical value as of 2007 might be about 10 nm.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] There are many other rule types not illustrated here.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] A *minimum area* rule is just what the name implies.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Antenna rules are complex rules that check ratios of areas of every layer of a net for configurations that can result in problems when intermediate layers are etched.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Many other such rules exist and are explained in detail in the documentation provided by the semiconductor manufacturer.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Academic design rules are often specified in terms of a scalable parameter, **λ**, so that all geometric tolerances in a design may be defined as integer multiples of **λ**.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] This simplifies the migration of existing chip layouts to newer processes.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Industrial rules are more highly optimized, and only approximate uniform scaling.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Design rule sets have become increasingly more complex with each subsequent generation of semiconductor process.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] The main objective of design rule checking (DRC) is to achieve a high overall yield and reliability for the design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] If design rules are violated the design may not be functional.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] To meet this goal of improving die yields, DRC has evolved from simple measurement and Boolean checks, to more involved rules that modify existing features, insert new features, and check the entire design for process limitations such as layer density.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] A completed layout consists not only of the geometric representation of the design, but also data that provides support for the manufacture of the design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] While design rule checks do not validate that the design will operate correctly, they are constructed to verify that the structure meets the process constraints for a given design type and process technology.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] DRC software usually takes as input a layout in the GDSII standard format and a list of rules specific to the semiconductor process chosen for fabrication.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] From these it produces a report of design rule violations that the designer may or may not choose to correct.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Carefully "stretching" or waiving certain design rules is often used to increase performance and component density at the expense of yield.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] DRC products define rules in a language to describe the operations needed to be performed in DRC.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] For example, Mentor Graphics uses *Standard Verification Rule Format* (SVRF) language in their DRC rules files and Magma Design Automation is using Tcl-based language.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] A set of rules for a particular process is referred to as a run-set, rule deck, or just a deck.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] DRC is a very computationally intensive task.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Usually DRC checks will be run on each sub-section of the ASIC to minimize the number of errors that are detected at the top level.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] If run on a single CPU, customers may have to wait up to a week to get the result of a Design Rule check for modern designs.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] Most design companies require DRC to run in less than a day to achieve reasonable cycle times since the DRC will likely be run several times prior to design completion.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/design-rule-checking] With today's processing power, full-chip DRCs may run in much shorter times as quick as one hour depending on the chip complexity and size.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] Initially, GDSII was designed as a stream format used to control integrated circuit photomask plotting.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] Despite its limited set of features and low data density, it became the industry conventional stream format for transfer of IC layout data between design tools of different vendors, all of which operated with proprietary data formats.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] It was originally developed by Calma for its layout design system, "Graphic Design System" ("GDS") and "GDSII".
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] GDSII files are usually the final output product of the IC design cycle and are handed over to IC foundries for IC fabrication.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] GDSII files were originally written on magnetic tape.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] The final deadline for IC designers is still called tape-out for this reason.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] Objects contained in a GDSII file are grouped by assigning numeric attributes to them including a "layer number", "datatype" or "texttype".
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] While these attributes were designed to correspond to the "layers of material" used in manufacturing an integrated circuit, their meaning rapidly became more abstract to reflect the way that the physical layout is designed.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] As of April 2008, many EDA software vendors have moved to the stream format OASIS, which replaced GDSII.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] For smaller designs, GDSII continues to be used today.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] As the GDSII stream format is a de facto standard, it is supported by nearly all EDA software.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] Besides the commercial vendors there are plenty of free GDSII utilities.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/gdsii] These free tools include editors, viewers, utilities to convert the 2D layout data into common 3D formats, utilities to fly through a 3D version, utilities to convert the binary format to a human readable ASCII format and program libraries.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] Originally the overall process was called tapeout, as historically early ICs used graphical black crepe tape on mylar media for photo imaging (erroneously believed to reference magnetic data—the photo process greatly predated magnetic media).
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] When using a standard process—where the interaction of the many chemical, thermal, and photographic variables is known and carefully controlled—the behaviour of the final integrated circuit depends largely on the positions and interconnections of the geometric shapes.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] Using a computer-aided layout tool, the layout engineer—or layout technician—places and connects all of the components that make up the chip such that they meet certain criteria—typically: performance, size, density, and manufacturability.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] This practice is often subdivided between two primary layout disciplines: analog and digital.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] The generated layout must pass a series of checks in a process known as physical verification.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] When all verification is complete, layout post processing is applied where the data is also translated into an industry-standard format, typically GDSII, and sent to a semiconductor foundry.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] The milestone completion of the layout process of sending this data to the foundry is now colloquially called "tapeout".
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] The foundry converts the data into mask data and uses it to generate the photomasks used in a photolithographic process of semiconductor device fabrication.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] In the earlier, simpler, days of IC design, layout was done by hand using opaque tapes and films, an evolution derived from early days of printed circuit board (PCB) design -- tape-out.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] Modern IC layout is done with the aid of IC layout editor software, mostly automatically using EDA tools, including place and route tools or schematic-driven layout tools.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] Typically this involves a library of standard cells.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/integrated-circuit-layout] The manual operation of choosing and positioning the geometric shapes is informally known as "polygon pushing".
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] The **layout versus schematic** (**LVS**) is the class of electronic design automation (EDA) verification software that determines whether a particular integrated circuit layout corresponds to the original schematic or circuit diagram of the design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] A successful design rule check (DRC) ensures that the layout conforms to the rules designed/required for faultless fabrication.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] However, it does not guarantee if it really represents the circuit you desire to fabricate.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] The need for such programs was recognized relatively early in the history of ICs, and programs to perform this comparison were written as early as 1975.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] These early programs operated mainly on the level of graph isomorphism, checking whether the schematic and layout were indeed identical.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] With the advent of digital logic, this was too restrictive, since exactly the same function can be implemented in many different (and non-isomorphic) ways.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] Therefore, LVS has been augmented by formal equivalence checking, which checks whether two circuits perform exactly the same function without demanding isomorphism.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] LVS checking software recognizes the drawn shapes of the layout that represent the electrical components of the circuit, as well as the connections between them.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] This netlist is compared by the "LVS" software against a similar schematic or circuit diagram's netlist.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] Reduction: During reduction the software combines the extracted components into series and parallel combinations if possible and generates a netlist representation of the layout database.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] A similar reduction is performed on the "source" Schematic netlist.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] Comparison: The extracted layout netlist is then compared to the netlist taken from the circuit schematic.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] If the two netlists match, then the circuit passes the LVS check.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] In most cases the layout will not pass LVS the first time requiring the layout engineer to examine the LVS software's reports and make changes to the layout.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] Opens: Wires or components that should be connected are left dangling or only partially connected.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] These must be connected properly to fix this.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] Missing components: An expected component has been left out of the layout.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] Parameter mismatch: Components in the netlist can contain properties.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] The LVS tool can be configured to compare these properties to a desired tolerance.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] If this tolerance is not met, then the LVS run is deemed to have a property error.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/layout-versus-schematic] A parameter that is checked may not be an exact match, but may still pass if the lvs tool tolerance allows it.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] In integrated circuit design, **physical design** is a step in the standard design cycle which follows after the circuit design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] At this step, circuit representations of the components (devices and interconnects) of the design are converted into geometric representations of shapes which, when manufactured in the corresponding layers of materials, will ensure the required functioning of the components.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] This geometric representation is called an integrated circuit layout.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] This step is usually split into several sub-steps, which include both design and verification and validation of the layout.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Modern day Integrated Circuit (IC) design is split up into *Front-end Design using HDLs* and *Back-end Design* or *Physical Design*.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] The inputs to physical design are (i) a netlist, (ii) library information on the basic devices in the design, and (iii) a technology file containing the manufacturing constraints.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Physical design is usually concluded by *Layout Post Processing*, in which amendments and additions to the chip layout are performed.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] This is followed by the wafer fabrication, the manufacturing process whereby designs are transferred via photomasks onto silicon dies which are then packaged into ICs.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Each of the phases mentioned above has design flows associated with them.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] These design flows lay down the process and guide-lines/framework for that phase.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] The physical design flow uses the technology libraries that are provided by the fabrication houses.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] These technology files provide information regarding the type of silicon wafer used, the standard cells used, the layout rules (like DRC in VLSI), etc.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] The physical design engineer (sometimes called physical engineer or physical designer) is responsible for the design and layout (routing), specifically in ASIC/FPGA design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Typically, the IC physical design is categorized into full custom, semi-custom, gate array, and FPGA design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] The design flow used depends strongly on the requirements.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Full custom design is the slowest and most expensive, but offers potentially the highest performance.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Semi-custom or ASIC is somewhat easier as the components have been pre-characterized, although in some cases the designer has the flexibility to design/modify design blocks from vendor provided libraries in ASIC.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] This flexibility is missing for flows using FPGAs (e.g.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Altera or Xilinx), which are the easiest to implement, as the chips are already fabricated.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] These offer the advantage of no fabrication time (a chip designed today can be running tomorrow) and by far the easiest debugging, but have the lowest performance and the highest cost per gate.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] There are detailed PD flows that are used depending on the tools used and the methodology/technology.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] The ASIC physical design flow uses the technology libraries that are provided by the fabrication houses.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Technologies are commonly classified according to minimal feature size.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Standard sizes, in the order of miniaturization, are *2μm, 1μm, 0.5μm, 0.35μm, 0.25μm, 180nm, 130nm, 90nm, 65nm, 45nm, 28nm, 22nm, 18nm, 14nm, etc.* They may be also classified according to major manufacturing approaches: n-Well process, twin-well process, SOI process, etc.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Physical design is based on a netlist which is the end result of the logic synthesis process.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Synthesis converts the RTL design, usually coded in VHDL or Verilog HDL, to gate-level descriptions which the next set of tools can read and understand.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] This netlist contains information on the cells used, their interconnections, area used, and other details.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] During the synthesis process, constraints are applied to ensure that the design meets the specified functionality and speed.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Only after the netlist is verified for functionality and timing it is sent for the physical design flow.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Note however that timing at this point is only an estimate, as the parasitics from the physical design are not yet known.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Partitioning is a process of dividing the chip into small blocks.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] This is done mainly to separate different functional blocks and also to make placement and routing easier.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Partitioning can be done in the RTL design phase when the design engineer partitions the entire design into sub-blocks and then proceeds to design each module.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] These modules are linked together in the main module called the TOP LEVEL module.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] This kind of partitioning is commonly referred to as Logical Partitioning.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] The goal of partitioning is to split the circuit such that the number of connections between partitions is minimized.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] The second step in the physical design flow is *floorplanning*.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Based on the area of the design and the hierarchy, a suitable floorplan is decided upon.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Floorplanning takes into account the macros used in the design, memory, other IP cores and their placement needs, the routing possibilities, and also the area of the entire design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Floorplanning also determines the IO structure and aspect ratio of the design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] A bad floorplan will lead to wastage of die area and routing congestion.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] In many design methodologies, *area* and *speed* are the subjects of trade-offs.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] This is due to limited routing resources, as the more resources used, the slower the operation.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Optimizing for minimum area allows the design both to use fewer resources, and for greater proximity of the sections of the design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] This leads to shorter interconnect distances, fewer routing resources used, faster end-to-end signal paths, and even faster and more consistent place and route times.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Done correctly, there are no negatives to floorplanning.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] As a general rule, data-path sections benefit most from floorplanning, whereas random logic, state machines, and other non-structured logic can safely be left to the placer section of the place and route software.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Data paths are typically the areas of the design where multiple bits are processed in parallel with each bit being modified the same way with maybe some influence from adjacent bits.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Example structures that make up data paths are Adders, Subtractors, Counters, Registers, and Muxes.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Earlier stages, when the placement is unknown, generally use a simple Wire Load Model (WLM), often an estimate based on fanout.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Placement uses more accurate RC values, typically estimated from the bounding box of all pins of a net, but without detailed routing.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] The goal of **clock tree synthesis** (**CTS**) is to insure proper operation of a clocked circuit, primarily by minimizing skew while controlling insertion delay.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] The clock is a single logical signal of high fanout before CTS, as shown in the picture.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] After CTS setup times should be met, and hold slack should be improved.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] A clock tree begins at a source (normally defined in an .sdc file) and ends at the clock pins of flip-flops.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] There are two types of stop pins known as *ignore* pins and *sync* pins.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] 'Don't touch' circuits and pins in front end (logic synthesis) are treated as 'ignore' circuits or pins at back end (physical synthesis).
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] 'Ignore' pins are ignored for timing analysis.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] If the clock is divided into multiple phases then a separate skew analysis is necessary.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Rigidity is the term coined in Astro to indicate the relaxation of constraints.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Higher the rigidity means tighter constraints.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] In **clock tree optimization** (CTO) clock can be shielded so that noise is not coupled to other signals.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] But shielding increases area by 12 to 15%.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Since the clock signal is global in nature the same metal layer used for power routing is used for clock also.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] CTO is achieved by buffer sizing, gate sizing, buffer relocation, level adjustment and HFN synthesis.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] We try to improve setup slack in pre-placement, in placement and post placement optimization before CTS stages while neglecting hold slack.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] In post placement optimization after CTS hold slack is improved.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] As a result of CTS lot of buffers are added.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Generally for 100k gates around 650 buffers are added.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] There are two types of routing in the physical design process, global routing and detailed routing.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Global routing allocates routing resources that are used for connections.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] It also does track assignment for a particular net.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Detailed routing does the actual connections.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Different constraints that are to be taken care during the routing are DRC, wire length, timing etc.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Physical verification checks the correctness of the generated layout design.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] Layout Post Processing, also known mask data preparation, often concludes physical design and verification.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/physical-design-electronics] It converts the physical layout (polygons) into mask data (instructions for the photomask writer).
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Before the introduction of VLSI technology, most ICs had a limited set of functions they could perform.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] An electronic circuit might consist of a CPU, ROM, RAM and other glue logic.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] VLSI enables IC designers to add all of these into one chip.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] The history of the transistor dates to the 1920s when several inventors attempted devices that were intended to control current in solid-state diodes and convert them into triodes.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Success came after World War II, when the use of silicon and germanium crystals as radar detectors led to improvements in fabrication and theory.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Scientists who had worked on radar returned to solid-state device development.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] With the invention of the first transistor at Bell Labs in 1947, the field of electronics shifted from vacuum tubes to solid-state devices.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] With the small transistor at their hands, electrical engineers of the 1950s saw the possibilities of constructing far more advanced circuits.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] However, as the complexity of circuits grew, problems arose.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] One problem was the size of the circuit.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] A complex circuit like a computer was dependent on speed.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] If the components were large, the wires interconnecting them must be long.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] The electric signals took time to go through the circuit, thus slowing the computer.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] The invention of the integrated circuit by Jack Kilby and Robert Noyce solved this problem by making all the components and the chip out of the same block (monolith) of semiconductor material.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] The circuits could be made smaller, and the manufacturing process could be automated.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] This led to the idea of integrating all components on a single-crystal silicon wafer, which led to small-scale integration (SSI) in the early 1960s, and then medium-scale integration (MSI) in the late 1960s.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] General Micro-electronics introduced the first commercial MOS integrated circuit in 1964.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] In the early 1970s, MOS integrated circuit technology allowed the integration of more than 10,000 transistors in a single chip.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] This paved the way for VLSI in the 1970s and 1980s, with tens of thousands of MOS transistors on a single chip (later hundreds of thousands, then millions, and now billions).
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] The first semiconductor chips held two transistors each.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Subsequent advances added more transistors, and as a consequence, more individual functions or systems were integrated over time.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] The first integrated circuits held only a few devices, perhaps as many as ten diodes, transistors, resistors and capacitors, making it possible to fabricate one or more logic gates on a single device.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Now known retrospectively as *small-scale integration* (SSI), improvements in technique led to devices with hundreds of logic gates, known as *medium-scale integration* (MSI).
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Further improvements led to *large-scale integration* (LSI), i.e. systems with at least a thousand logic gates.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Current technology has moved far past this mark and today's microprocessors have many millions of gates and billions of individual transistors.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] At one time, there was an effort to name and calibrate various levels of large-scale integration above VLSI.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Terms like *ultra-large-scale integration* (ULSI) were used.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] But the huge number of gates and transistors available on common devices has rendered such fine distinctions moot.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Terms suggesting greater than VLSI levels of integration are no longer in widespread use.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] In 2008, billion-transistor processors became commercially available.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] This became more commonplace as semiconductor fabrication advanced from the then-current generation of 65 nanometer processors.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Current designs, unlike the earliest devices, use extensive electronic design automation and automated logic synthesis to lay out the transistors, enabling higher levels of complexity in the resulting logic functionality.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Certain high-performance logic blocks, like the SRAM (static random-access memory) cell, are still designed by hand to ensure the highest efficiency.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Structured VLSI design is a modular methodology originated by Carver Mead and Lynn Conway for saving microchip area by minimizing the interconnect fabric area.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] This is obtained by repetitive arrangement of rectangular macro blocks which can be interconnected using wiring by abutment.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] An example is partitioning the layout of an adder into a row of equal bit slice cells.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] In complex designs this structuring may be achieved by hierarchical nesting.
[src:physical-design-vlsi/very-large-scale-integration] Structured VLSI design had been popular in the early 1980s, but lost its popularity later because of the advent of placement and routing tools wasting a lot of area by routing, which is tolerated because of the progress of Moore's law.
